article.description:
Paul Pierce scored 21 of his 28 points in the second half and made 16 foul shots to lead the Boston Celtics to a
93-83 victory over the New Orleans Hornets on Wednesday night.
article.headline: Pierce scores 21 of 28 points in second  half

images.name: Mashburn_Jamal 030108 Inline
images.caption: Jamal Mashburn and the Hornets are scrambling to move up in the conference standings.

article.linkText: Pierce's strong second half pushes Celtics over Hornets
article.story:
NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Paul Pierce, mindful of the Boston Celtics' 3-point struggles in a loss this week to Washington, made sure his team got inside against the New Orleans Hornets. Pierce shot only 5-of-14 but scored 16 from the foul line, and his 28 points led Boston to a 93-83 victory over the Hornets on Wednesday night. "I wanted to just stay aggressive, mix it up and get to he line," said Pierce, who had 21 of his points in the second half. "We learned from our last game when we took too many 3-pointers, and I just wanted to make a concerted effort to go to the basket." Boston, which was 8-of-32 from 3-point range against Washington on Monday, improved marginally to 9-of-28 against New Orleans. But Boston was able to make three straight from long range -- two by Tony Delk and one by Pierce -- during a 16-2 fourth-quarter run to put the game away. The Hornets, who led 70-69 after three quarters, went nearly eight minutes without a field goal (0-for-13) after Elden Campbell's baseline jumper gave New Orleans a 74-73 lead with 8:50 left. "In the fourth quarter, when we needed it most, it got away from us," Hornets guard David Wesley said. "They scrambled, they really gambled and it paid off. We didn't make them pay." Celtics coach Jim O'Brien said his club's strong defense during a decisive late-game run reminded him of the way Boston played in advancing to the Eastern Conference finals last season. "This was a great defensive effort by our starters in the fourth quarter," he said. Eric Williams added 17 for Boston and Delk had 16. Antoine Walker scored 14 after a slow start. Jamal Mashburn led New Orleans with 21 points, while Courtney Alexander scored 20 and Wesley 17. Baron Davis (back injury) missed his fourth consecutive game. Hornets coach Paul Silas said his club missed Davis badly in the fourth quarter. "I never make excuses, but it's a fact we're not the same ballclub when he's not playing," Silas said. "You take 17 points out of your lineup and you try to manufacture points and it's tough. You do the best you can and try to weather the storm until he gets back and then go forward." After hitting only three of their first 12 3-pointers, Boston hit three in four possessions in the middle of the third quarter. The third, by Eric Williams, tied the game at 65. Boston then took its first lead since the first quarter when Pierce, who had 10 points in the third, hit a free throw after the Hornets were called for a defensive 3-second violation. Wesley responded with a 3-pointer, the Hornets' third of the quarter, and Alexander hit a pair of free throws to give the Hornets the lead back heading into the final period. New Orleans' disastrous fourth-quarter shooting ruined a strong start in which the Hornets hit their first seven shots and went 57 percent for the first quarter in taking a 27-20 lead. Mashburn hit his first four shots for eight points with half the quarter still to go. The Celtics started 7-for-11 and trailed only 21-20 after a pair of free throws by Walter McCarty, but Boston didn't have a field goal for the last half of the period. After falling behind by as many as 11, Boston climbed back within 46-42 at halftime after New Orleans shot 5-for-21 in the second quarter. Walker, who didn't have a point through the first quarter-and-a-half, hit a 3-pointer and twice worked his way inside on the dribble for baskets. Shammond Williams' layup got Boston as close as 42-40. Game notes
The Celtics last played in New Orleans on March 12, 1985, in what was a home-away-from-home game for the Atlanta Hawks. A little more than 10,000 packed the University of New Orleans Lakefront Arena to watch Larry Bird score 60 points. ... Wednesday marked the second time the Celtics have faced New Orleans this season and the second time Boston did not have to face standout guard Baron Davis. Davis sat out the first game of his career during the Hornets' 95-86 loss in Boston on Dec. 1. Bothered by back spams stemming from a herniated disk, Davis left in the first quarter of a game against Indiana on Dec. 31 and has missed New Orleans' four subsequent games. Silas said Davis hopes to return Friday when the Hornets host Detroit. ... Pierce has been to the foul line at least 10 times in 10 of his last 12 games.
